    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-11-08T05:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-11-08T05:40:00-05:00" n="153"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                <head>153. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Poland</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d153fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_Pol1">POL</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_Pol1">POL</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>.
                        Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Warsaw</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-11-08T10:40:00+00:00">November 8, 1971,
                        1040Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3748. Subj: Conversation with Party Chief <persName corresp="#p_GE1"
                        >Gierek</persName>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In course Soviet Embassy reception November 6, new Polish
                        Ambassador-designate to <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TW2">Trampczynski</persName> arranged for me to speak
                        with <gloss target="#t_PZPR1">PZPR</gloss> Chief <persName corresp="#p_GE1"
                            >Gierek</persName>. Latter was extremely warm in his comments, toasting
                        the American people, <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>-Polish ties, and
                        expressing hopes for success of <persName corresp="#p_TW2"
                            >Trampczynski</persName>ʼs mission. <persName corresp="#p_GE1"
                            >Gierek</persName> dwelt on his desire to expand trade between <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss> and Poland said he was most grateful for
                        Presidentʼs decision to grant license for catalytic cracker.<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d153fn2">See <ref target="#d151">Document 151</ref>.</note> He
                        was pleased Secretary <persName corresp="#p_VJ1">Volpe</persName> had
                        visited Poland and said Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_JP1"
                            >Jaroszewicz</persName> had told him of his extremely interesting talk
                        with <persName corresp="#p_VJ1">Volpe</persName>.<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d153fn3">
                            <persName corresp="#p_VJ1">Volpe</persName> visited Poland for talks in
                            November 1971. A memorandum of his November 3 conversation <persName
                                corresp="#p_JP1">Jaroszewicz</persName> is in the Department of
                            State, Polish Desk Files: Lot 74 <gloss target="#t_D1">D</gloss> 440,
                                <persName corresp="#p_VJ1">Volpe</persName> Visit.</note>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GE1">Gierek</persName> commented that <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss> and Poland had great historic traditions in
                        common, but that he hoped “new and even better traditions” could be
                        established in future.</item>
                    <pb facs="0412" n="368" xml:id="pg_368"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Observing <persName corresp="#p_GE1">Gierek</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_TW2">Trampczynski</persName> together, it seemed evident
                        that, as we have heard, <persName corresp="#p_TW2">Trampczynski</persName>
                        is well regarded by <persName corresp="#p_GE1">Gierek</persName> and has
                        good personal relationship with him. <persName corresp="#p_GE1"
                            >Gierek</persName> stressed in his conversation that <persName
                            corresp="#p_TW2">Trampczynski</persName> would have “direct, personal
                        channel” in reporting to him on matters of special interest.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>In other conversations during evening, I spoke with Politburo member
                        Tejchma, who reportedly concentrates on foreign affairs field, and with
                        Central Committee foreign affairs expert Ryszard Frelek. Tejchma was
                        forthcoming on <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>-Polish relations and said
                        he thought prospects were good for improvement in political as well as
                        economic field. Frelek called catalytic cracker decision a “turning point”
                        and forecast important favorable developments in <gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >US</gloss>-Polish relations in next year. He mentioned in particular
                        that visit by <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> astronauts would be welcome
                        in 1972.<note n="4" xml:id="d153fn4">There was no visit by <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> astronauts to Poland in 1972.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">Comment</hi>. Change in atmospherics is especially
                        striking when compared with similar Soviet reception November 1970, when it
                        was impossible to talk with top leaders and all one could get out of
                            <persName corresp="#p_GW1">Gomulka</persName> was a glum handshake and
                        no comment.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWJJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Stoessel</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
